 of Islamic art and anyone interested in the ways of perceiving and understanding the arts more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aArtxPsychology. 0aCommunication in art. 0aIslamic artxThemes, motives. 0aVisual perception. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  a.  aAbbasid(s).  aAfrica.  aAli.  aBaghdad.  aBenin.  aCairo.  aChina.  aEgypt.  aGranada.  aGreece.  aIndia.  aIran.  aIraq.  aIslam, architecture.  aMamluks.  aMatisse, Henri.  aModigliani, Amedeo.  aOttomans.  aParis.  aSafavids.  aSpain.  aTimurids.  aWarhol, Andy.  amuqarnas.  arepresentation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertThe A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Packagez978311129290840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691252773?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691252773423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691252773/original  a978-3-11-129290-8  The A. W. Mellon Lectures in the Fine Arts eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles